title: Deuteron induced reactions on Ho and La: Experimental excitation functions and comparison with code results

x4freetext: Deuteron induced reactions on Ho and La: Experimental
excitation functions and comparison with code results

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.311, p.102 (2013)

x4codes.hlp: Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: Irradiations of
165Ho and 139La targets was performed through stacked
foil irradiation followed by high resolution gamma
spectrometry. Stacks were irradiated at cyclotron of
the Universite Catholique in Louvain la Neuve (LLN)
with nominal incident energy of deuterons 50 MeV and
the accelerator of Tohuku University, Sendai, nominal
incident energy 40 MeV. For irradiation at 50 MeV a
stack consisting of 22 Ho foils (29.2 micro-m)
together with Sm (25-23 micro-m) was
prepared, interleaved with Al (98 micro-m)
monitor/degrader foils. The beam current was kept
constant at 120 nA (+-5%) during the 3960 s. In the
experiment at 40MeV a stack containing 10 Ho foils
and eight other elements used for separate
evaluations (Rh, Au, Yb, MnCuNi alloy, MoRe alloy),
together with Al energy degrader and monitor foils
were irradiated for 1800 s with a deuteron beam of 64
nA in a Faraday-like target holder under He gas
atmosphere for cooling. In the experiments on La the
stack was composed of 23 La foils (97 micro-m)
together with Tl/Cu (electroplated) targets, evenly
distributed Al monitor-degrader foils (266 micro-m)
were inserted and the irradiation with 50 MeV
incident deuteron beam lasted for 2310 s at a nominal
115 nA current. The average thickness of the foils
was determined by weighing large, geometrically well
defined samples and using accepted mass density for
the pure material. The obtained uncertainty of 2% on
the average thickness has to be increased to 5% for
uncertainty on individual foils allowing for local
variations over the larger samples. Three series of
spectra were recorded for the irradiated samples.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nuclear Data Services (Doc. series of NDS), No.1211 (2001)

x4freetext: , Al+d
The uncertainty on the median energy in the
foils includes the cumulative effects of uncertainty of
incident beam energy, uncertainty of stopping power of
each foil due to thickness variation and  straggling
effects.
The uncertainty on the cross section values
are estimated in the  standard way following the
recommendations of the ISO-guide as the square root of
the quadratic summation of the independently
contributing parameters. Uncertainty of time parameters
is not included.
surface density of target nuclei(5%),
incident charged particle flux (5%),
nuclear decay and branching data(5%)
detector efficiency (3-5%)
statistical and peak fitting (1-8%)
This approach results in an overall uncertainty
of 12-15% for the radionuclides studied.
The experimental data were compared to the
results of the theoretical model codes TENDL-2012,
ALICE-D and EMPIRE-D.
The measured experimental data were compared to
those found in the literature.
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
Entry was checked by the corresponding author.
